     John Pickens
     1:205/33
                     My Wife's New Couch

     "They also serve, who only stand and wait."

     Certainly this is true of the wives of FidoNet Sysops.  While
     some spouses endure the much fabled Wednesday night Poker game,
     the sports addicted couch potato, or antique automobile
     restoral, the wife of a FidoNet Sysop finds that she is sharing
     her husband with that most demanding of mistresses, The Bulletin
     Board System!

     Yes, the BBS sings her siren song to the Sysop.  Enticing,
     seducing, entreating him to spend more time at the task of
     attaining that ever elusive goal (that is more a state of mind
     than an actual state of being) which can be summed up in the
     words, "There!  I've finally gotten it the way I want it, now I
     don't have to do any more, it can run itself!"

     The wife of a FidoNet Sysop (ok, ok, EVERY Sysop, but I like to
     indulge myself in the small conceit that FidoNet Sysops are far
     more dedicated in their task, the creme de la creme if you
     will) finds that she must come to terms with one of life's
     simple truths:  No matter how much time, no matter how much
     money her husband spends on his Bulletin Board, it will NEVER be
     enough.  There will always be one more screen to create, a
     little more tweaking to do, another hard drive to buy, another
     (insert favorite BBS activity here).

     Picture the following, fellow Sysop, and tell me honestly this
     hasn't happened in your home:

     It's late at night and you are working on the board.  It may be
     a new utility you're trying to install, or perhaps catching up
     on your mail.  It doesn't really matter what you're doing, the
     point is you are INVOLVED!  The last thing you want at this
     point is to be interrupted or have to stop what you're doing.
     Your wife is on her way to bed (after spending the entire
     evening alone in front of the tube, after all, you've been
     busy) and she asks when you're coming to bed.  Granting that
     your brain registers the fact that someone has said something,
     you reply absently that you'll be to bed in a few minutes.  When
     you actually do get to bed you silently hope that your wife
     doesn't wake up to see you hitting the sack at 2:30 am - 3 hours
     after you last spoke to her.

     FidoNews 7-20                Page 2                   14 May 1990


     Sound familiar?

     How about this?

     Your powers of persuasion and creativity are pushed to the
     limit as you explain to your wife just exactly why you need to
     spend several hundred dollars for an HST modem, a VGA card &
     monitor, or any of the score of goodies that immediately come to
     mind.

     No, the conscientious Sysop does not have an easy life, but the
     wife of a Sysop has an even more difficult task.  She gives up
     time with her husband, abandoning him to an avocation which, in
     most cases, she understands very little and cares about even
     less.  Not easy to do, but done out of love.

     This is not to say that there are not women who share their
     husbands interest.  Au contraire!  As a matter of fact in Net
     205 there is one wife who has developed such an interest in the
     BBS hobby that she now runs the slickest and most popular board
     in the area and is the NEC to boot!  She has a real passion to
     make her BBS the very best it can be and you can see that care
     from the moment you log on (and our hats are off to ya, Sam!).

     My heartfelt thanks to the wives of the FidoNet Sysops, and to
     my own wife in particular, for putting up with this strange
     preoccupation which borders on obsession.  You smile bravely and
     encourage us in this expensive and time consuming hobby.  My own
     wife has never asked once why in the world I want to spend
     thousands of dollars and devote an endless amount of time to
     entertain total strangers.  No doubt she's wondered, but has
     never asked.  Without the support of our spouses in this odd
     and delightful hobby, the boards would be a far less interesting
     place to be.

     About the title:  My friend sits, admiring my new system.  I
     won't bore you with the details, but it is a superfine machine
     which anyone would be proud to own.  My friend turns to me and
     says, "This is a really nice setup!"

     My wife, in the dining room, is watching us.  Upon hearing my
     friend's comment she pulls on her mask of patient long-suffering
     and informs our guest, "That's my new couch."

     Lastword:  OK, before I'm flamed to death by the female Sysops
     out there let me say that I wrote this from a man's perspective
     and that's the way it is.  There are a lot of BBS's run by the
     fair sex and without exception I have found them to be first
     rate.  But tell me, if your husband, boyfriend or whatever does
     not share your interest, don't they sometimes resent the time
     you spend with your system?                I'm outta here.
