     The Electronic Pyramid Scam --

     Makecash, Cash-4u, Fastbuck, Easy$, etc.

     I have DELETED several of these from my upload area recently.
     I am even seeing the text files included in otherwise innocuous
     uploads such as BBS lists.  These are nothing more than PYRAMID
     MARKETING schemes outlawed years ago.

     To be fair, these modern electronic chain letters avoid the
     rules related to the postal chain letters because they offer a
     product for sale.  However, there is no direct mechanism in
     place to avoid the 4th level of a 'network marketing'
     structure, which is illegal.  NETWORKING is the modern name for
     a controlled pyramid organization. Pyramid organizations are
     quite legal out to the 3rd level, but not the fourth.

     Short of calling the police, I can't imagine a way to stop this
     kind of abuse.  I'd love to here your ideas on the subject. (
     But only if they agree with mine ! )


     486 On the March --

     There seems to be quite a rush of 486 PCs coming out this year.
     It's always fun to see your old computers become more worthless
     all the while doing more than they ever did.  The trend towards
     faster PCs has followed pretty closely an old rule about
     microprocessor development, ie. that micros double in speed and
     density every two years.  My particular case is a perfect
     example.

     In July 1985 I purchase my first AT, a Compaq 286 8Mh portable,
     for $5000.  It's still in service, running 24 hours a day as
     124/6119.  Of course, it's got 8 times the original disk space.

     In July 1987 I purchased my first 386, a Compaq 386 16Mh for,
     yes $5000.  Now I did add lots of memory to it, but it's still
     running, in fact, I'm writing this on it while it runs
     124/6120.

     This trend ( '85 286-8, '87 386-16 ) would lead me to believe
     that in 1989 I could purchase a 386 33Mh for $5000.  This was,
     in fact, true.  However, due to the imminent release of the
     486, I determined that a wait was in order.  I now see that a
     1990 486-25 for $5000 is possible.

     FidoNews 7-20                Page 24                  14 May 1990


     Following the trend further, 1991 should bring a 486-33 at our
     benchmark price, and 1993 must be the year of the 586 or better
     at some 60 Mh.  Since I've skipped a year, I'm due a hot new
     machine !


     MS C 6.0 --

     Representative of the goodies which arrived recently, MS C 6 is
     in use here.  I've been reading about _fastcall, the advisor,
     new Codeview options and better optimization options.  True to
     Earth day, Microsoft sent quite a bit less paper, although it
     seems complete and concise.  "Just use the old binders" !  I
     have been looking at the /W4 maximus warnings switch, whew,
     what a mess I have.

     Oracle 5.1C arrived with VPIC support.  This should mean I can
     run Oracle's protected interface along with expanded memory
     drivers, even Desqview.  It works.  I have to get Oracle's
     library and MS' new C libraries integrated at work.  Finger's
     crossed.

     QEMM 5.0 is a welcome addition.  Comes with a really
     interesting SYSTEM STATUS program, Manifest.  I have a Compaq
     386, but I have to run the NOCOMPAQFEATURES switch ?!?  Don't
     even know why, but I do and it works.  I do run Desqview
     constantly.

     Math Rabbit ( what, a game ) got installed immediately.  My son
     really liked Reader Rabbit, and he loves this.  When you win a
     round with the rabbit on the tightrope, he does one of three
     dances.  In the third dance, he does this Michael Jackson
     'Reverse Moon Walk Glide' that can't be adequately described.
     Terrible graphics ( CGA ) but Kevin loves it.


     Clean That Office, or Else --

     Honey threw a fit.  It really was a mess.  I started Saturday
     afternoon by purchasing a couple of nice chairs and another
     table top.  The rolling chair made it possible to put computers
     behind and in front of me, and the additional work space will
     be taken up by a new machine coming in for a client.

     I started Sunday morning, carrying everything out to the living
     room floor.  Honey grabbed the kid disappeared for a few hours.
     By 11 ( right on schedule ) the computers went off line, and
     the room was nearly empty.  A quick clean and it was time to
     bring it all back in.  Done by 1.

     Do you have many stacks of old papers on your floor ?  Each
     one, no matter the topic, containing some obscure BBS utility
     document printout, usually 50 pages long ?  Do you have
     thousands of diskettes that you have no idea of the contents ?
     Here is another summer job for computer literate kids. Pay em a
     few bucks an hour to catalog all those disks.
     FidoNews 7-20                Page 25                  14 May 1990


     Honey returned home and was quite pleased.  She let me put up
     the swimsuit calendar that her grandmother gave me for
     Christmas.  I can't wait for July !


